&lt;h2 id=&#34;undergraduate-texts&#34;&gt;Undergraduate texts&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I recommend you have a good undergraduate intermediate microeconomics text for developing intuition. I use the 4th edition of Varian&amp;rsquo;s undergraduate text (&amp;ldquo;Baby Varian&amp;rdquo;), but the 7th edition is what has been on reserve.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Varian (2006), &amp;ldquo;Intermediate Microeconomics : A Modern Approach,&amp;rdquo; Norton, 7th Edition [Baby Varian].&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;math-references&#34;&gt;Math references&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For math references, I find the appendices of MWG often inaccessible and am not aware of others that are comprehensive. I do, however, like KrepsNew&amp;rsquo;s appendices on Real Analysis and Convexity. I am a huge fan of the book listed below on optimization by Dixit as well as Simon and Blume&amp;rsquo;s math for economists book. I will integrate parts of Binmore&amp;rsquo;s and Velleman&amp;rsquo;s books in class and suggest them as background preparation for anyone without a background in Real Analysis. I have made available a list of &lt;a href=&#34;https://motoyoshihara.github.io/&#39;/courses/606/math/&#34;&gt;Real Analysis&lt;/a&gt; topics from Corbae et al. with which you should endeavor to be familiar. Corbae et al. presents the material in a more complex way than what is needed for our purposes, so the list is useful as a reference but I don&amp;rsquo;t suggest using this as a text to learn the concepts.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Dixit (1990), &amp;ldquo;Optimization in Economic Theory,&amp;rdquo; Oxford University Press, Second Edition.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Simon and Blume (1994), &amp;ldquo;Mathematics for Economists,&amp;rdquo; Norton.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Binmore (1982), &amp;ldquo;Mathematical Analysis: A Straightforward Approach,&#39;&#39; Cambridge University Press, Second Edition.*&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Velleman (2019), &amp;ldquo;How to Prove it: A Structured Approach,&amp;quot;&#39; Cambridge University Press, Third Edition.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Corbae, Stinchcombe and Juraj (2009), &amp;ldquo;An Introduction to Mathematical Analysis for Economic Theory and Econometrics,&#39;&#39; Princeton.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The library will have all of these on reserve when they resume physical reserves in the fall. Two of the books are available in electronic form in the library catalog; they are marked with asterisks. Between now and the end of August, I have arranged for the rest of the books to be placed at the front desk for “In Library Use Only.” You can go to the desk and ask for &amp;ldquo;books for Professor Buzard.&amp;rdquo; You won&amp;rsquo;t be able to check them out, but can look over them inside the library and then you must return the books to the front desk.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
